            <scopecontent>
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                                 <p>On November 29, 1854, when Abraham Lincoln first ran for U.S. Senator, he sought the support of Hugh Lamaster [Lemaster] (1798-1870), editor of a short-lived newspaper in Fulton County, Illinois.<emph render="super">1</emph> On November 29, 1860, when Lincoln was President-elect, Lamaster wrote his son Joseph, believing that &quot;now is my time&quot; to ask for an appointment for him in &quot;any Land Office, Marshallship, or any other office under <emph render="underline">Old Abe</emph>.&quot;</p>
                                 <p>Although Lamaster anticipated help from Republican Congressman William Kellogg, and planned to consult with both Lincoln and Richard Yates at the inauguration of Yates as Illinois governor on January 14, 1861, apparently nothing came of the proposed appointment.</p>
                                 <p>Hugh Lamaster&#039;s letter alludes to the sectional crises of 1820, 1832, and 1849-50, during which, he wrote, blacks in the South escaped to the North, only to be caught by fugitive slave laws, the &quot;expenses paid by the Free States.&quot; In time, he anticipated the power of the South would shift to the &quot;Great West.&quot;</p>
                                 <p>The Lamasters were landowners in Fulton Center, a crossroads in Putnam Township, between Cuba and Lewistown in Fulton County, Illinois.<emph render="super">2</emph></p>
                                 <p>The collection also includes a letter of February 2, 1867, from Hugh Lamaster, written in Baltimore on a trip east, to his wife in Nebraska City, Nebr., and a letter of July 19, 1858, from E. D. Rice, written in Lewistown, Ill., to his children, mostly regarding family and friends.</p>
                                 <p>The collection was acquired by the Rare Book and Manuscript Library and transferred to the Illinois History and Lincoln Collections in 2014.</p>
                                 <p>Notes:</p>
                                 <p>1. Abraham Lincoln to Hugh Lemaster (November 29, 1854) in <emph render="italic">Collected Works of Abraham Lincoln</emph>, vol. 2 (New Brunswick, N.J: Rutgers University Press, 1953), 289. A copy of original letter is available at <extref linktype="simple" audience="external" show="embed" actuate="onrequest" href="http://presidentialcollections.org/catalog/200816">http://presidentialcollections.org/catalog/200816</extref>.</p>
                                 <p>2. <emph render="italic">Atlas Map of Fulton County, Illinois </emph>(Davenport, Iowa: Andreas, Lyter &amp; Co., 1871), 88.</p>
                        </scopecontent>
            


